    													    <div class="post_img main_img">
					        <img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/fist.png" alt="" class="entry_post" itemprop='image'/>
					    </div>
					    <!-- IMAGE CREDIT -->
				        													
				<div class="post_content_body_wrapper">
    			<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				<div class="sponsored"><a href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/747060/women-of-war-by-suzanne-cope/" target="_blank" class="external">Via Dutton</div></a>					<h1 class="post_title" itemprop="headline">
					What Are the Revolutionaries Reading? Activists Recommend Essential Texts					</h1>
					<h3>Suzanne Cope Talks to Darlene Okpo, Jacob A.C. Remes, Julie Schweitert Colazzo and Steff Reed</h3>
				</div>
								<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
					<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/suzannecope/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Suzanne&nbsp;Cope</span></a></div>
					<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
					<div class="publish_date">July 3, 2025</div>
				</div>
				<div class="social_links">
										<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=What+Are+the+Revolutionaries+Reading%3F+Activists+Recommend+Essential+Texts&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fwhat-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
					<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fwhat-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts%2F&t=What+Are+the+Revolutionaries+Reading%3F+Activists+Recommend+Essential+Texts"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
									</div>
									<!-- Begin each blog post -->
					<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
						<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
					    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
								<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
							        
									<span itemprop="articleBody"><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">One day while Bianca Guidetti Serra—a </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">staffetta</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">, or courier, for the Italian resistance during World War II—was delivering news and supplies to the anti-fascist partisan army in the Alps, she received a request from their </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">commissar</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">. Emanuele Artom was a small, thin young man—not as strong as his fellow resistance fighters. But he was a student and a gifted teacher, and was thus given one of the most important roles among the partisans: the commissar was in charge of the soldiers’ education and mental well-being. Emanuele asked Bianca to bring books the next time she made the long and difficult trek from Turin. He said to Bianca, “I think when it comes to rebuilding the country, they know nothing about parties, about trade unions, about democracy. We run the risk of things coming back to the way they were.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Despite knowing that she would then have to ride with this heavy load up the steep Alpine switchbacks and through Nazi-contested land, Bianca readily agreed. She knew the importance of political education, particularly for her fellow Italians who had grown up under Mussolini’s Fascist regime, where the educational curriculum reflected the regime’s biased worldview to suppress resistance, causing many books and newspapers with dissenting or alternate viewpoints to be censored or banned. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bianca remembered, too, the book that had a profound impact on her own political awakening. Her parents were left-leaning, but like so many other Italians, hid their views from their children for fear of retribution from Mussolini’s loyalists. But Bianca found a copy of Leon Trotsky’s autobiography </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">My Life </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">on her father’s shelf—and it opened her eyes to the thoughts and experiences of a revolutionary. This would inspire her first political acts a few years later when she organized friends to tear down propaganda posters to protest Mussolini’s Racial Laws that limited the rights of Jewish people in Italy. Later she read works quietly provided to her by her fellow partisans, including Marx’s writing on the power of the working class, which would then inspire her own efforts during the war to organize mass strikes around Nazi-occupied Italy.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">That day Bianca returned home from her mission in the mountains and carefully chose a small library to bring on her next trip: books that she believed might inspire and inform the rag-tag group of young men who were risking their lives for the promise of a free Italy after the war—like she was. But Emanuele would never receive them. Days later he and others, including Bianca’s fiancé, were forced from their camp by a Nazi raid. Emanuele, not as physically fit as the others, was captured and killed. </span></p>
<p><span class="pullquote"><span style="font-weight: 400;">No one walks into a movement fully formed, but we can all help create something powerful, one step at a time, through education and connection with community.</span></span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">After the war, his memory would be honored by the publication of his diaries. In Italy this became essential reading about the experiences of Jewish partisans during the war. Only recently translated into English, it is now available under the title </span><a href="https://store.yadvashem.org/en/these-thoughts-of-mine-diaries-of-an-italian-jewish-partisan-january-1940february-1944" class="external" target="_blank"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">These Thoughts of Mine: Diaries of an Italian Jewish Partisan, January 1940–February 1944</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></i></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">I draw from Bianca’s story under Nazi occupation in my narrative nonfiction book, </span><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593476000" class="external" target="_blank"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Women of War: The Italian Assassins, Spies, and Couriers Who Fought the Nazis</span></i></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. In the four female protagonists in the book, political education appears as a key element to their path to join the anti-fascist resistance. Anita Malavasi, who grew up on a farm in the region of Reggio Emilia before moving to the city of Reggio, remembered her grandfather reading stories by Dostoyevsky and other Russian novelists to the children in the warmth and privacy of the barn—works she didn’t realize were considered highly subversive under the Fascist regime. “What did we know about politics?” Anita said about her generation of women in particular. “With Fascism, you could only read what target gave you and you didn’t even have the right to make comments.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When she became active in the resistance, she joined a women’s group called the GDD, which had chapters across occupied Italy and focused on political education and organizing resistance support and actions. Through the education and discussion with these women, she had her own political awakening. “At that point we understood that we could change our future. We understood that we had to be more than partisans, that we had to acquire consciousness about our role in the resistance.” After Anita was arrested by Fascist officers under suspicion of involvement in the resistance, she escaped to the mountains where she fought with the partisan army until the end of the war. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Unlike others facing the same Nazi occupation in various countries, the Italians were not fighting to return to the life they had before the war. Rather, they were also engaged in reimagining the new Italy they wanted post-war—one in which they had political power and agency, more rights for workers and women, and freedom of thought and expression. It was only through political education that they could begin to conceive of—and fight for—this future. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">But of course, Italian partisans were not the only revolutionaries to embrace the power of political education. This has been endemic to so many other movements for political and social change. In my book</span><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781641604529" class="external" target="_blank"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Power Hungry</span></i></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, I wrote about women in the Black Independence movement. From Freedom Summer, which had Freedom Schools teaching children and adults about Black history and excellence, as well as constitutional rights—to the Black Panther Party, which held required PE (political education) classes where they read and discussed Franz Fanon, Malcolm X, W.E.B. Du Bois, Richard Wright and others, education was also core to their understanding of, and dedication to, the racially and economically just future they were fighting for.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Occupy Wall Street, which was primarily an economic justice movement that began in 2011 with an occupation of Zuccotti Park near Wall Street in downtown Manhattan, had their own library and reading list that included </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The People’s History of the United States </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">by Howard Zinn and </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">America Beyond Capitalism</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> by Gar Alperovitz</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">. And more recently, a number of groups have put together more informal reading lists for the Black Lives Matter movement, which includes </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The New Jim Crow</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> by Michelle Alexander, </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Fire Next Time</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> by James Baldwin, among many others. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">No one walks into a movement fully formed, but we can all help create something powerful, one step at a time, through education and connection with community. To help create an even more robust list of books, I’ve asked other leaders from diverse specialties and communities, below, to share readings they believe are also instructive for this moment in history. </span></p>
<p>*</p>
<p><b>Darlene Okpo</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">the owner of Adanne Bookshop in Brooklyn that centers Black voices, joy, and liberation. Okpo says, “We’re more than just a shop, we’re a cultural and creative hub where community meets resistance, and reading is a revolutionary act&#8230;.Political education is at the core of how we keep each other informed, grounded, and mobilized, and books have always been one of our greatest tools for that.”</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256385" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle.png" data-orig-size="701,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="freedom is a constant struggle" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle-210x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256385" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle-210x300.png" alt="" width="210" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle-210x300.png 210w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle-42x60.png 42w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle-35x50.png 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-is-a-constant-struggle.png 701w" sizes="(max-width: 210px) 100vw, 210px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781608465644" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Freedom Is a Constant Struggle</i></a> by Angela Y. Davis</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Because liberation is global. This book connects Ferguson to Palestine and reminds us that movements are interconnected, and none of us are free until all of us are.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256379" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/we-do-this-til-we-free-us/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us.png" data-orig-size="645,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="we do this til we free us" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-194x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256379" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-194x300.png" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-194x300.png 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-32x50.png 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us.png 645w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781642595253" class="external" target="_blank"><i>We Do This ‘Til We Free Us</i></a> by Mariame Kaba</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Because abolition is not a metaphor. Kaba gives us real language, real tools, and real hope for what justice can look like without cages.</span></p>
<p>*</p>
<p><b>Jacob A.C. Remes</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> teaches labor history and disaster studies at NYU and is on the bargaining committee of Contract Faculty United &#8211; UAW, the largest union of private-sector, full-time, non-tenure track professors in the U.S. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256384" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/on-strike-for-respect/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect.jpg" data-orig-size="268,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="on strike for respect" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256384" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect-201x300.jpg" alt="" width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/on-strike-for-respect.jpg 268w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780252064548" class="external" target="_blank"><i>On Strike for Respect: The Clerical and Technical Workers&#8217; Strike at Yale University, 1984-85</i></a> by Toni Gilpin, Gary Isaac, Dan Letwin, and Jack McKivigan</strong></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">What can unions do when everything, from the state to the very structures of the workplace, are arrayed against them? This pamphlet of a book explains how to organize and win under what we now call neoliberalism, taking a successful strike by secretaries at Yale in the mid 1980s as its case study.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256382" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/another-politics/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics.jpg" data-orig-size="267,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="another politics" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256382" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/another-politics.jpg 267w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780520279025" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Another Politics: Talking Across Today&#8217;s Transformative Movements</i></a><i> </i>by Chris Dixon</strong></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Political theory from the bottom up; Dixon interviewed dozens of organizers in anti-racist, anti-authoritarian, and anti-capitalist movements about what they believed, what they did, and what they fought for.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256380" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/many-are-the-crimes/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes.jpg" data-orig-size="659,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="many are the crimes" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256380" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes-198x300.jpg" alt="" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/many-are-the-crimes.jpg 659w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316774703" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Many Are the Crimes: McCarthyism in America</i></a> by Ellen Schrecker</strong></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A new red scare is breaking up interracial social movements under the cover of anti-antisemtism; what better time to read this definitive history of McCarthyism and how it worked as a public-private partnership to expel radical politics from mainstream society and domesticate the New Deal. </span></p>
<p>*</p>
<p><b>Julie Schweitert Colazzo, </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">founder of Immigrant Families Together and co-author of </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Book of Rosie</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256379" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/we-do-this-til-we-free-us/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us.png" data-orig-size="645,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="we do this til we free us" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-194x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256379" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-194x300.png" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-194x300.png 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us-32x50.png 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/we-do-this-til-we-free-us.png 645w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781642595253" class="external" target="_blank"><i>We Do This &#8216;Til We Free Us</i></a> by Mariame Kaba</strong></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Some folks read Scripture; I read Mariame Kaba. While the focus of this book is about abolitionist practices, as much of Kaba&#8217;s wider body of work (both on and off the page) is, it&#8217;s a primer on how to imagine change and new systems and structures more broadly. At its core, it&#8217;s about why and how we build community, how we stitch networks of care and concern so that they have the tensile strength to survive hard moments, political and otherwise. You know&#8230;kind of like the moment we&#8217;re living now. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256378" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/baldwin-collected-essays/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays.jpg" data-orig-size="210,331" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="baldwin collected essays" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays-190x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256378" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays-190x300.jpg" alt="" width="190" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays-190x300.jpg 190w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays-38x60.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/baldwin-collected-essays.jpg 210w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 190px) 100vw, 190px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://www.loa.org/books/121-collected-essays/" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Collected Essays of James Baldwin</i></a> published by the Library of America</strong></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There are lots of folks who&#8217;ve crossed the threshold who I wish could be with us today, and James Baldwin is chief among them. His writing in this collection is </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">so </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">utterly of the moment in which he lived, but it is also still timely. That could devastate a reader. But what will prevent them from tumbling into the abyss is Baldwin&#8217;s clear-eyed assessment of the American political condition—the human political condition—and his advice about what we do to live with that and become and do better. </span></p>
<p>*</p>
<p><a href="http://www.iamsteffreed.com/" class="external" target="_blank"><b>Steff Reed</b></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is a musician, cultural organizer, and scholar whose work bridges the arts, political education, and liberation theology to mobilize communities toward healing, justice, and collective liberation.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256377" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power.png" data-orig-size="708,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="myth and propaganda of black buying power" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power-212x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256377" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power-212x300.png" alt="" width="212" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power-212x300.png 212w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power-42x60.png 42w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power-35x50.png 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/myth-and-propaganda-of-black-buying-power.png 708w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 212px) 100vw, 212px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9783031265488" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Myth and Propaganda of Black Buying Power</i></a><i> </i>by Jared A. Ball</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is a critical text that shatters neoliberal myths and illusions-elucidating the ways in which hegemonic Black capitalist myths are weaponized to pacify and neutralize the Black political imagination. Ball surgically dismantles one of the most enduring myths in Black political life—that consumer spending equals liberation—and in doing so, he clears the fog of capitalist propaganda to make room for organizing, material analysis, and actual movement-building rooted in class struggle and collective liberation.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256376" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take.png" data-orig-size="647,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="you only get what youre organized to take" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take-194x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256376" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take-194x300.png" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take-194x300.png 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take-32x50.png 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/you-only-get-what-youre-organized-to-take.png 647w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780807008645" class="external" target="_blank"><i>You Only Get What You&#8217;re Organized To Take</i></a> by Liz Theoharis and Noam Sandweiss-Back</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">You Only Get What You’re Organized to Take</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is a powerful blueprint for how faith organizing must be tied to political education and collective class struggle. Liz Theoharis and Noam Sandweiss-Back offer a sharp, clarion call to action that connects moral vision with material demands—reminding us that collective liberation isn’t given, it’s taken through disciplined movement-building rooted in faith and justice.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256375" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/freedom-dreams/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams.png" data-orig-size="647,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="freedom dreams" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams-194x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams.png" class="size-medium wp-image-256375 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams-194x300.png" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams-194x300.png 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams-32x50.png 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/freedom-dreams.png 647w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780807007037" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Freedom Dreams: The Black Radical Imagination</em></a> by Robin D.G. Kelley</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Freedom Dreams: The Black Radical Imagination<span style="font-weight: 400;"> is crucial reading for artists and cultural workers who see their craft as part of the collective struggle for collective liberation. This book invites readers to reclaim the Black radical imagination as a tool for world-building—reminding us that visionary art and collective dreaming are not just aesthetic acts, but revolutionary practices.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">__________________________________</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256341" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-are-the-revolutionaries-reading-activists-recommend-essential-texts/women-of-war/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war.jpeg" data-orig-size="298,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="women of war" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-256341" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war-199x300.jpeg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/women-of-war.jpeg 298w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593476000" class="external" target="_blank">Women of War The Italian Assassins, Spies, and Couriers Who Fought the Nazis</a> <em>by Suzanne Cope is available from Dutton, an imprint of Penguin Publishing Group, a division of Penguin Random House, LLC.</em></p>
