							<div class="post_wrapper author">
								<div id="about_the_author">
									<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/suzannecope/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Screen-Shot-2021-11-19-at-1.08.20-PM-100x100.png" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Screen-Shot-2021-11-19-at-1.08.20-PM-300x300.png 2x" alt="Suzanne Cope" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
									<div class="description author withsidebar">
										<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/suzannecope/">Suzanne Cope</a></h6>
										Suzanne Cope is a scholar and narrative journalist, and is the author of <em>Power Hungry: Women of the Black Panther Party and Freedom Summer and Their Fight to Feed a Movement</em>. Her work on themes of political and social change, feminism, food, and culture has appeared in <em>The New York Times</em>, <em>The Atlantic</em>, <em>Los Angeles Review of Books</em>, <em>Food & Wine</em>, BBC, <em>Washington Post</em>, <em>Aeon</em>, and others.  She is a professor at New York University.																			</div>
								</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
							</div>
